    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Acidosis is a great term to understand the severity of the situation. When lactic acid builds up to high levels, it can lead to a condition called metabolic acidosis. This is when the body's pH levels become too acidic, causing a range of symptoms, including muscle fatigue, cramping, and pain.\n\nNow, regarding the damage to muscle tissue, it's a bit more complicated. When lactic acid levels get too high, it can lead to a condition called rhabdomyolysis, which is the breakdown of muscle tissue. This can cause the release of myoglobin, a protein found in muscle cells, into the bloodstream. Myoglobin can then bind to red blood cells, causing them to become misshapen and lose their ability to carry oxygen.\n\nIn severe cases, this can lead to a condition called compartment syndrome, where the pressure inside the muscle compartment becomes too high, cutting off blood flow and oxygen delivery to the muscle tissue. This can cause permanent damage to the muscle fibers and lead to chronic pain, weakness, and even long-term muscle damage.\n\nHowever, it's worth noting that most cases of muscle burning during intense exercise are not severe enough to cause permanent damage. The muscle tissue can usually recover on its",
